resids = residuals(model)

     main = "Residuals vs. Fitted Values",
     ylab = "Residuals", 
     xlab = "Fitted Values", col = "Light Blue")
abline(h = 0, col = "red", lty = 2)

qqnorm(resids, main = "QQ Plot of Residuals")
qqline(resids, col = "red")

# acf of residuals
acf(resids, main = "ACF of Residuals")

Based on the qqplot, the residuals do not deviate too far from the normal distribution. Additionally, the residuals are mostly evenly distributed and centered around 0, indicating little to no heteroscedasticity. However, the ACF plot shows some initial dependencies between the residuals, with a sharp decrease as the lags increase. This may indicate a problem with the model specification (perhaps there is a time series dependence that is not being accounted for with a linear regression), but the other model diagnostics indicate a well-specified model so we can proceed with caution.

Question 6: Which Model Gives Best Result in Terms of White Noise

Based on the DW test stat, only model 6 (ARMA(2,2)) has a stat close to 2, indicating little to no autocorrelation. Based on AIC and BIC, model 6 also has the lowest values compared to the other models, indicating a better fit. According to the LJ test results, all of the models have p-values less than 0.05, indicating that the residuals are autocorrelated. However, model 6 has the highest p-value, potentially indicating that there’s less autocorrelation in it’s residuals and the residuals are closer to resembling white noise compared to the other models. Therefore, model 6 will give the best results with the residuals being close to white noise based on AIC, BIC, and the limited amount of autocorrelation found from the DW test.

Question 7: Bootstrap Residuals

# Bootstrap lin reg residuals 

set.seed(44)

resids_bsp = bld.mbb.bootstrap(model$residuals, n = 500)

# Bootstrap ARMA coefficients for ARMA(1, 0, 1)

ar1_coefs = numeric(500)
ma1_coefs = numeric(500)

# Loop through each bootstrap, fit model, and store
for (i in 1:500) {
  tmp = arima(resids_bsp[[i]], order = c(1, 0, 1))
  
  ar1_coefs[i] = tmp$coef["ar1"]
  ma1_coefs[i] = tmp$coef["ma1"]
}
hist(ar1_coefs, main = "Distribution of AR(1) Coefficients",
     xlab = "AR(1)",
     col = "Light Blue",
     breaks = 20)

hist(ma1_coefs, main = "Distribution of MA(1) Coefficients",
     xlab = "MA(1)",
     col = "Light Blue",
     breaks = 20)

The coefficients resemble Normal distributions due to the bell shapes. With 500 bootstrap samples (much larger than n=30), the Central Limit Theorem indicates that the distribution of the coefficients will tend to normality as the sample size increases.

Question 8: Bootstrapped Confidence Intervals

# CI for bootstrapped ARMA(1,1) model
ar1_ci <- quantile(ar1_coefs, c(0.025, 0.975))
ma1_ci <- quantile(ma1_coefs, c(0.025, 0.975))

print("Bootstrapped ARMA(1,1) Confidence Intervals")
## [1] "Bootstrapped ARMA(1,1) Confidence Intervals"
cat("Bootstrapped 95% CI for AR(1): ", ar1_ci, "\n")
## Bootstrapped 95% CI for AR(1):  0.9128133 0.9246364
cat("Bootstrapped 95% CI for MA(1): ", ma1_ci, "\n")
## Bootstrapped 95% CI for MA(1):  0.6003456 0.7438013
# CI for original ARMA(1,1) model
ci2 <- confint(arma_1_1)

print("Original ARMA(1,1) Confidence Intervals")
## [1] "Original ARMA(1,1) Confidence Intervals"
cat("95% CI for AR(1): ", ci2["ar1", ], "\n")
## 95% CI for AR(1):  0.8682903 0.959134
cat("95% CI for MA(1): ", ci2["ma1", ], "\n")
## 95% CI for MA(1):  0.6999069 0.8066302

The bootstrapped confidence intervals are narrower than the original model’s coefficients. This is expected since the bootstrapped confidence intervals are from a larger sample size (due to the resampling), increasing the chance of being closer to the true value due to less uncertainty. The original model’s confidence interval is based on just one model’s results so it captures more uncertainty, therefore, it is wider.
